# Near-Degenerate Tiny-Trigger Stress Fails All Three Step-4 Gates On One Fixed Exact Ledger

Status: `VERIFIED` anti-family role with `INFERRED` frozen ledger and failure mechanisms

The genuine obstruction-facing Step-4 anti-family is
`F_DT(delta, eta)` with `0 < eta << delta <= 1/12` on the same frozen window,
packet object, spectator partition, and thresholds used by the positive test
sheet.

On the normalized ledger `int_I D_on = 1`, the desired channels stay live but
become sharply misordered:

- the clock remains macroscopic;
- the late rotor and next-shell legs collapse to `delta` and `delta^2`;
- and the trigger never crosses on the fixed window, with
  `t_clk = 1/5`, `t_trig > 1`, and `t_rot`, `t_next` undefined.

At the same time the spectator load stays macroscopic:
`L_mirror = 1/8`, `L_companion = 1/6`, `L_feedback = 1/6`, `L_cross = delta`,
so `L_tot = 11/24 + delta`.
That overloads the frozen leakage sheet because both companion and feedback
exceed their `1/12` class budgets and `L_tot > 3/8`.

Therefore all three Step-4 gates fail on one fixed exact ledger without any
threshold retuning:

- `Template-Defect Near-Closure` fails because the late rotor / next-shell
  hierarchy collapses while spectator mass stays large.
- `Windowed Spectator-Leakage Budget` fails by explicit classwise overload.
- `Delayed-Threshold Itinerary` fails because the tiny trigger never becomes
  active soon enough to complete the declared ordered itinerary.

This is the anti-circuit verdict that matters operationally:
the informative adverse family is not zero-activity cancellation but a live
exact packet whose late desired channels collapse, whose spectators overload,
and whose trigger remains mistimed on the frozen Step-4 sheet.

